<HEADLINE>
FT  06 FEB 93 / Court approves restructuring of O&amp;Y Canadian operations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A RESTRUCTURING plan for Olympia &amp; York Developments was approved by an
Ontario judge last night, ending nine months of court protection for the
collapsed Canadian property developer.
O&amp;Y, which was the world's biggest developer prior to seeking bankruptcy
protection for its Canadian operations last May, will emerge still nominally
owned by the Reichmann family, who built up the company over 25 years, but
controlled by its creditors.
The plan covers only O&amp;Y's Canadian operations. It does not affect Canary
Wharf, the project in London's Docklands, which has also been under the care
of administrators since last May. Canary Wharf's future is currently the
subject of negotiation between the administrators, a group of international
banks and the UK government.
Under the Canadian plan a new company will be formed. It will be known as
O&amp;Y Properties, and will concentrate on property management. O&amp;Y's Canadian
buildings, as well as its US properties and its non-property investments,
will remain under the umbrella of O&amp;Y Developments.
As part of yesterday's court order, Mr Justice Robert Blair sanctioned the
appointment of an administrator who is expected to preside over the gradual
dismantling of the company and the seizure of several of its buildings by
creditors. The restructuring involves about two thirds of O&amp;Y's total debt
of CDollars 13.5bn (Pounds 7bn).
The administrator is expected to be Mr Robert Lowe, an insolvency expert in
the Toronto office of auditors Coopers and Lybrand.
The future of O&amp;Y's US properties, comprising about 20 buildings, depends on
the outcome of talks between the company and lenders to the various
buildings.
Mr Paul Reichmann, who masterminded O&amp;Y's expansion in the 1970s and 1980s,
resigned earlier this week from the board of the US subsidiary.
Mr Justice Blair said he was satisfied that the plan was 'fair and
reasonable'. Under the restructuring proposals, most secured creditors will
be allowed to seize their collateral on 30 days notice.
</TEXT>
