<HEADLINE>
FT  06 FEB 93 / Travel: Night walks in winter - Practical Traveller
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGELA WIGGLESWORTH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MY FIRST experience of winter walking was in the mountains above the small
Swiss town of Lenzerheide, 17 kilometres south of Chur, where the tourist
office has produced a map of the 35km of forest paths kept open during
winter months. The sun shone and the air was crisp.
The only sound was our own footsteps. There were stops for hot chocolate in
mountain cafes and, in the evenings, the spectacle of 'full moon skiing' -
instructors skiing down the mountains carrying flaming torches.
Several companies are offering UK winter walking holidays. Some, involving
small groups, offer guides; others allow you to walk independently but have
accommodation arranged.
Acorn Activities (tel: 0432-357335), in Hereford, offers guided walks in the
Wye valley and the Black mountains. Prices vary according to farmhouse or
hotel accommodation.
Alternative Cornish Holidays (tel: 0841-540147) runs independent walking
holidays along the north Cornish coast from Bude to Bedruthan Steps, where
huge breakers come crashing up the wide beaches (Pounds 255 a week).
Several local councils have produced books listing guided walks in their
areas. Some of the walks are free, for others you pay a charge of Pounds 1
or Pounds 2. Exploring Sussex (Pounds 1), for example, from East Sussex
County Council (tel: 0273-481654) lists 336 circular weekday and weekend
walks and cycle rides.
For those who like to walk on their own and return to the comfort of a
luxury country house hotel and a gourmet meal, there is Congham Hall, a
Georgian manor house near Kings Lynn, Norfolk (0485-600250). Maps for local
walks are supplied and the owners are happy to pick up exhausted walkers at
the end of the day and return them to the same spot the next.
The 17th century, 15-bedroomed Cotswold House Hotel in Chipping Campden
(0386-84033) has the Cotswold Way (90 miles to Bath) starting on its
doorstep. And Seckford Hall at Woodbridge in Suffolk (0394-785678), where
Queen Elizabeth I is said to have held court, has beautiful panelled rooms,
low-beamed ceilings, carved doors and a swimming pool in a courtyard barn.
Further afield, Explore (0252-319448) takes walkers to the Taurus mountains
and the Berber villages of Morocco; the Ramblers Association (0707-331133)
visits Madeira, the Himalayas and the Hawaiian islands; and you can explore
Argentina with Waymark Holidays (0753-516477).
If you fancy walking by night rather than day, Bavaria has the answer: take
a guided walk in the snow with torches to light the way and mulled wine at
the end of the journey. Details from the German Tourist Office
(071-495-3990).
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
    MAZ  Morocco, Africa.
    PTZ  Portugal, EC.
    DEZ  Germany, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
