<HEADLINE>
FT  06 FEB 93 / London Stock Exchange: Banks under pressure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE, JOEL KIBAZO and PETER JOHN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FEARS that NatWest Bank was planning to call on investors for extra cash set
nerves jangling in the banking sector. The rumours came at a time when,
according to merchant bank Robert Fleming, the sector had hit an 17-year
relative high against the market and gave an ideal opportunity to take
profits.
Mr Nick Dobby of Flemings said there was talk that NatWest could be
considering a rights issue in the region of Pounds 1bn. But he added; 'There
is no loan growth at the moment, the bank's capital ratios are well in
excess of the regulatory minimum and investors would be likely to focus on
Barclay's Pounds 921m cash call in 1988 which did not prove a very efficient
investment.'
NatWest shares fell 12 to to 448p with 14m traded. However, it was also
suggested that, if NatWest needs to raise cash, Barclays needs it more and
the latter's shares fell 16 to 429p. Meanwhile, Lloyds fell 11 to 537p
hampered by speculation that it was lining up a bid for one of three old
candidates, TSB, Royal Bank of Scotland or Standard Chartered. One might
have expected the bid candidates to improve but the whole sector was held
back by a feeling that base rates will not be cut any further in the
short-term.
Queens Moat deal
The sale by the joint managing director of Queens Moat Houses of half his
equity holding in the hotel group was followed by a heavy fall in the share
price. The sale came just ahead of the closed period, during which company
officers are prohibited from dealing in the stock market. Queens Moat, whose
shares have traced an erratic path recently, will announce results at the
beginning of April.
The shares were marked back sharply in August. They hit a low of 27 1/2 p
when the board revealed an unexpected jump in debt, in spite of improved
profits and increased dividend.
Yesterday, Mr Martin Marcus sold 500,000 shares at 57 1/2 p and a further
600,000 at 57p, a slight discount to the prevailing market price. The shares
fell heavily but later rallied to close at 53 1/2 p, a fall of 4 1/2 .
Turnover was a chunky 4.8m.
Clifford approach
An announcement from Clifford Foods that it had been approached by a
potential suitor prompted excitement in the food manufacturing sector.
Market fingers pointed at Unigate, with analysts close to the company
hinting that the two may have held discussions recently. Others which might
be interested could include Avonmore, the Irish dairy group, Northern Foods,
French concern BSN and MD Foods of Denmark.
Clifford is family-controlled and any offer would have to be agreed. Its
concentration in the south-eastern liquid milk market would fit into
Unigate's acquisitive milk-orientated strategy. Analysts put a price tag of
around Pounds 50m on Clifford, a sum easily affordable by Unigate without
resorting to issuing paper. Clifford ordinary voting shares jumped 85 to
505p, with the 'A' shares up 32 at 216p. Unigate slipped 5 to 325p and
Northern a penny to 262p.
Merchant bank Hambros had a volatile share performance ahead of an
announcement that it had won a court case brought it in Oslo by the
Norwegian Guarantee Institute. The shares were down 58 earlier as investors
thought Hambros had lost the case but they finished a net 15 up on the day
at 313p.
Water utility shares lifted as analysts said their average dividend growth
was likely to outpace that of the market and stressed the companies'
defensive qualities. Thames Water was up 10 at 497p, Severn Trent 8 at 474p
and Anglian Water 7 at 488p. Panmure Gordon's Mr Angelos Anastasiou
estimates real dividend growth for the market at nine per cent over the next
five years compared with 19 per cent for the water sector.
Fisons lifted 6 to 233p following an announcement from the company that it
has signed a marketing deal. The deal is not significant in itself but lends
growing support to the growing view that the company is more viable. There
was also a return of lingering bid speculation.
Croda International jumped 13 to 263p on hopes for a new multiple sclerosis
treatment. However, the company sought to temper optimism saying clinical
trials had net begun yet.
Worries over the possibility of VAT being imposed on food in the Budget
again put food retail stocks under a cloud. Argyll Group declined 6 to 374p,
J Sainsbury 10 to 558p and Tesco 4 to 250p.
Rank Organisation was hit by two sets of switch advice, with Goldman Sachs
advising a move into Ladbroke and Hoare Govett preferring Thorn EMI. Shares
in the latter added 8 to 861p, while Ladbroke rose 3 to 203p and Rank
recovered to close a penny adrift at 713p.
Analysts declared themselves little better off after a visit to a WH Smith's
Do It All facility. Speculation had been rife that the retailer may have
taken the opportunity to announce a restructuring of the loss-making
venture. Smith shares rose but then retreated to close a penny off at 425p.
Confirmation that Lord King had relinquished his role as chairman of British
Airways was well received in the market and the shares jumped 5 to 293p. One
analyst said; 'What we were looking for was minimum disruption of a good
management.' The shares closed 8 up at 296p, with volume reaching 5.5m.
Shares in freight container and trailer rental company Tiphook fell 17 to
336p after several brokers downgraded profit expectations. The company's
broker UBS Phillips &amp; Drew reduced its current-year estimate by Pounds 5m to
Pounds 75m, and the following year's figure by the same amount to Pounds
85m. NatWest Securities went from Pounds 80m to Pounds 72.5m, for this year
and shaved the 1994 figure by Pounds 10m to Pounds 85m.
Yield buying, greater confidence over the dividend and and improved outlook
for the property sector all helped P&amp;O buck the market trend to add 5 at
570p.
Profit-taking in ERF Holdings saw the shares fall 23 to 232p. It was also
profit-takers in British Aerospace which saw the shares fall 8 to 270p at
the day's worst. But bargain hunters later in the day helped it close 2
lighter at 276p. Dealers said recent currency movements would benefit Siebe
and the shares gained 10 to 489p.
Royal Insurance added 6 at 282p on talk that SG Warburg Securities was
recommending the stock.
