<HEADLINE>
FT  06 FEB 93 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FEARS of a rights issue in the banking sector led to a decline in stock
index futures that was only curbed by a strong opening on Wall Street,
writes Joel Kibazo.
The March contract on the FT-SE started firmly at 2,877 and advanced on good
buying, reaching 2,897 by around 10am. The contract had been expected to
continue moving forward but around mid-morning speculation of a rights issue
in the banking sector surfaced.
This caused a retreat in March with sentiment also hurt by continuing
worries in the food sector of an imposition of VAT on food.
The early gains in New York, however, helped the contract claw back some of
the earlier falls and March finished at 2,871, just ahead of Thursday's
close, with turnover reaching 11,251 lots.
The traded options saw business of 32,639 lots, down on Thursday's 43,859
lots. Some 7,027 lots were dealt in the FT-SE 100 option and among the stock
options, GEC traded 4,118 contracts with Trafalgar House and Barclays also
busy.
