<HEADLINE>
FT  06 FEB 93 / US still doubtful on Bosnia peace plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM, REUTER and AP
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Bill Clinton said yesterday he remains reluctant to back the
Bosnian peace proposals of Mr Cyrus Vance and Lord Owen, but asked for more
time to formulate a new US policy for the war-torn region.
'The United States at the present time is reluctant to impose an agreement
on the parties to which they do not agree, especially when the Bosnian
Moslems might be left at a severe disadvantage if the agreement is not
undertaken in good faith by the other parties and cannot be enforced
externally,' Mr Clinton said in Washington yesterday.
The new president and his foreign policy advisers promised to make Bosnia
their highest priority when they took office two weeks ago, but they have
since found it difficult to formulate a policy that lives up to Mr Clinton's
promises to take a tougher line against Serbian aggression in Bosnia.
US officials believe the Bosnian Moslem government will never accept the
Vance-Owen plan, which would divide Bosnia into 10 semi-autonomous
provinces. Critics of the Clinton position say the main reason they will not
do so is because the US has led them to hope it will obtain a better deal
for them.
Mr Brian Mulroney, the Canadian prime minister, suggested to Mr Clinton at
the White House yesterday that the US could usefully back the 'hard and
constructive work' of Mr Vance and Lord Owen while adding substantial
improvements in the areas of human rights and war crimes.
Also in Washington, Mr Klaus Kinkel, the German foreign minister, added his
voice to those suggesting to the US that the Vance-Owen plan, while not
perfect, was 'the last chance we have of bringing about a solution by
peaceful means'.
Reuter adds: Fighting between Serbs, Moslems and Croats raged across Bosnia
yesterday before 11th-hour peace talks were due to open at the United
Nations.
AP adds: German Chancellor Helmut Kohl said yesterday he favours lifting a
UN weapons embargo on Bosnia-Hercegovina.
