<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 93 / Van Miert warns energy utilities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
EC competition commissioner Karel van Miert has warned European governments
and energy utilities that they should end monopolies on intra-EC imports and
exports of gas and electricity.
He told a Brussels conference on Wednesday evening that he favoured security
of energy supply - one argument put forward by energy utilities resisting
liberalisation - but attempting to define security of supply in purely
national terms was 'out of date'.
His comments echoed those of his predecessor, Sir Leon Brittan, now trade
commissioner, but Mr Van Miert's tone was much less confrontational.
For example, he did not threaten to use special Commission powers to attack
national monopolies. Draft legislation to allow consumers to buy electricity
and gas from any EC supplier is stalled at ministerial level because of
government opposition.
The conference - inspired by French utilities in the fields of water,
energy, telecommunications, road, rail and postal services - yesterday
launched a European charter aimed to promote benefits of the French model of
public utilities.
Mr Jacques Delors, European Commission president, welcomed the initiative as
the beginning of a new era for public service companies. Utilities had
suffered a series of unjustified 'frontal attacks' in recent years based on
'dogmatic and ideological' objections, he said.
French public monopolies believe the appointment of Mr Van Miert, a Belgian
Socialist, as competition commissioner will ease ideological pressure.
During the conference, Mr Jean-Louis Bianco, French housing, transport and
infrastructure minister, said he hoped Mr Van Miert would introduce a
'different spirit'.
Mr Van Miert said he did not consider the application of competition policy
alone would automatically make things better; he repeated his view that
other elements - like social and environment policy - should be taken into
account.
But he warned the audience: 'If you think I'm a sort of anti-Sir Leon,
forget it.'
</TEXT>
