<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 93 / UK Company News: Telegraph sells Trinity stake and buys into
Canada
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY and PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TELEGRAPH has sold its near-13 per cent stake in Trinity International,
the publishing group, for Pounds 26.8m and is buying half of the 22.6 per
cent stake in Southam, the Canadian newspaper group acquired recently by Mr
Conrad Black's Hollinger Group.
Mr Black, chairman of the Telegraph, built up the interest in Trinity,
publisher of the Liverpool Post and Echo in 1990, almost certainly in the
hope that the Telegraph would one day be able to increase its stake or even
take over the group. Like Mr Black, Trinity has a string of small papers in
Canada.
Hollinger paid CDollars 259m (Pounds 141m) for the stake in Southam,
Canada's largest newspaper publisher with 18 daily papers and interests in
business information services and trade publications. The Telegraph is to
pay half of that.
The sale of the Trinity holding to a wide range of UK institutional
shareholders, suggests that Mr Black has conceded that he had little chance
of winning control of the company in the foreseeable future.
There are only 12 voting shares, and they are held by directors. The unusual
structure was created in 1904, when the company was first incorporated, to
protect its then Liberal political line against potential Conservative
predators.
Mr Black, through Hollinger, bought 5.6m of the shares at prices ranging
from 170p to 200p in July 1990.
The final total of 8.74m shares was sold, it is believed, at 320p, producing
a pre-tax profit on the deal of Pounds 6.5m.
Last May the Trinity stock was acquired by the Telegraph as part of a
reorganisation prior to the listing of the Telegraph on the Stock Exchange.
The money will be put on deposit.
Mr Philip Graf, Trinity's managing director designate, commenting on the
sale yesterday, said: 'We are very pleased. We understand the shares have
been placed with a wide spread of institutions.'
Trinity said it keeps its voting structure under review, but it is clear it
does not feel under any real pressure to change it at the moment.
In March, Trinity was able to raise some Pounds 23m from a rights issue to
help pay for its Pounds 45m purchase of Scottish and Universal Newspapers.
Participation by the Telegraph in Southam is subject to the approval of
Southam's independent directors and the Telegraph's shareholders, other than
Hollinger. Hollinger holds a 68.1 per cent stake in the Telegraph.
The statement said the Telegraph's cash resources, together with the Pounds
26.8m proceeds of the Trinity sale yesterday would be sufficient to cover
about 75 per cent of the cost of the proposed joint venture interest.
Hollinger paid CDollars 18.10 a share for its stake in Southam, shares of
which were yesterday trading at CDollars 15 1/4 .
Last month Mr William Ardell, Southam's chief executive, said the Canadian
group planned to forge closer links with Mr Black's other international
publishing investments, the Daily Telegraph in the UK and Australia's
Fairfax Holdings.
Mr Ardell said that he foresaw opportunities to create products, including
improvements to existing papers.
</TEXT>
