<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 93 / Shares rise worldwide on revival hopes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HOPES that the surprise cut in German interest rates will help revive the
fragile European economy pushed up share prices on most world markets
yesterday.
It lifted share prices in the US, where investors see a strengthening of
America's economic revival by increased demand for its exports. On Wall
Street, the Dow Jones Industrial Average closed at a record 3,416.74, up
42.95.
The Bundesbank's move quelled fears that the European exchange rate might be
in for another turbulent period after last weekend's forced devaluation of
the Irish punt.
The most immediate gainers were the Danish krone and the French franc
following a rush of funds out of D-Marks. Both the Danish and French
currencies had, until yesterday, been pinned relatively close to their ERM
floors by the strong D-Mark.
Sterling, which has been steadily losing ground since last week's base rate
cut, gained sharply against the D-Mark. By last night the system's hard core
currencies - the D-Mark, French franc and the Benelux currencies - were all
trading close to one another in the ERM grid. However there was some
disappointment at the relatively small cut.
The European bond markets showed little change on the day, although German
government bonds finished slightly lower. The best performers included the
Milan and Paris bourses, both of which gained about 1.5 per cent, while the
German rate cut move triggered an after-hours trading flurry on the
Frankfurt exchange.
The London stock market reacted cautiously. The FT-SE 100 index of leading
shares gained 26 points before the Bundesbank announcement to reach a high
of 2,900.1, the first time the index had breached the 2,900 mark. But the
index slipped back to a close of 2,865.9, down 7.9 on the day, after
widespread profit-taking.
The FT-SE Eurotrack 100 index, which tracks prices of leading company shares
across Europe, closed below the day's highs at 1,113.35, for a gain of
16.32.
Sterling rose to DM2.395 immediately after the Bundesbank announcement,
closing in London slightly lower at DM2.39 for an overall gain of 3 pfennigs
on the day. The pound closed against the dollar at Dollars 1.445, just over
1 cent up on the day. In New York sterling closed at DM2.3897 and Dollars
1.4415.
</TEXT>
