<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 93 / Observer: Semantics
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The mooted Anglo-French wedding between retailers Kingfisher and Darty has
run into problems already. While Kingfisher's statement merely mentioned
'discussions', Darty's went further and said the talks concerned a
'rapprochement'.
The British news services checked their dictionaries, translated the word as
a 'link-up', and rumours that Kingfisher was merely discussing taking a
stake in Darty started to spread. In the end Darty had to swallow its pride
and admit that its 'rapprochement' was more akin to the Anglo-Saxon
definition of the word takeover. Didn't Yves Saint-Laurent use the same
linguistic ploy before it was gobbled up by Sanofi?
