<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Heimat (BBC 2, 11.20) continues its slow but gripping march through the
history of Germany in the 20th century.
Continuing on the Teutonic theme, there is Sam Peckinpah's harrowingly
realistic film Cross of Iron (BBC 1, 11.00). Set on the Eastern Front, the
film looks at the nature of warfare through the eyes of four German
soldiers.
But with that exception, this is an evening with so little - beyond another
dose of The Bill (ITV, 8.00) - to recommend it that a good book is surely
the answer.
However, if you are absolutely determined to spend it square-eying and fancy
something in the current affairs line, there is Public Eye (BBC 2, 8.0). The
film outlines the tough measures which from April, under the Child Support
Act, will in theory be implemented to catch those many back-sliding fathers
who won't - or can't - disgorge the maintenance they owe for their children.
If, by some unlikely chance, the so-called cult American comedy series
Nurses (C4, 10.00) has attracted followers, they should take note that
tonight sees an end of the bad business.
</TEXT>
