FT  05 FEB 93 / Technology (Worth Watching): Mario the plumber goes
educational
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DELLA BRADSHAW
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Love 'em or hate 'em, few have found it possible to ignore computer games
for Nintendo consoles. Now the lovable hero of many of these games, Mario
the Brooklyn plumber, has turned his attention from high adventure to
something more educational - painting and composing music.
Mario Paint enables would-be artists to draw, paint and animate characters
on the screen using a mouse, the controller familiar to many personal
computer users. Nintendo says this is the first computer game to be
controlled by a mouse rather than a joystick. (The mouse is included in the
Pounds 59.99 price of the package, and plugs directly into the Nintendo
16-bit Super NES console.)
If the console is also connected to a video cassette recorder, pictures or
animated sequences created on the screen can be recorded. Music can also be
added, by arranging in sequence a number of picture elements which appear on
the screen. A picture of a jumbo jet, for example, would represent one note,
a flower another and so on. Nintendo: Japan, 075 541 6111; UK, 0703 651010.
