<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 93 / Parliament and Politics: Portillo to review public spending
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Michael Portillo, chief secretary to the Treasury, is set to announce the
most sweeping review of public spending since the early 1980s.
As rising public sector borrowing increasingly threatens ministers' hopes of
avoiding tax rises, Mr Portillo will in the next few weeks announce plans
for re-assessing Whitehall departments' long-term expenditure priorities.
It is expected to be the most fundamental review since Lord Howe, the former
Chancellor, ordered a similar study after the Conservatives took power in
1979. The aim then was to cut public spending in real terms.
Mr Portillo's review, expected to last at least a year, will look at
spending in the hope of paving the way for further income tax cuts before
the general election.
A likely early target is the Pounds 76bn social security budget which now
accounts for about a third of government spending compared with less than a
quarter in 1979-80. Defence and transport are other possibilities.
Mr John Major is determined to take a tougher line on public spending as the
Treasury forecasts that the public sector borrowing requirement will reach
Pounds 37bn this financial year and Pounds 44bn in the following financial
year.
The cabinet agreed in principle to the review last May but work was delayed
while Mr Portillo concentrated on November's Autumn Statement.
He is expected to set out a programme of work - probably indicating the
departments to be subject to scrutiny first as well as the overall
objectives.
Mr Major hinted at the review in his speech to the Carlton Club on
Wednesday. He said it was, 'dangerously easy for the state to settle into
habits of spending which outlast their purpose and outrun their budgets. And
to avoid that happening, it is necessary from time to time to re-examine
long term trends in expenditure.'
The prime minister said that to make progress towards lower personal
taxation, 'we must keep firm control of inflation and take a rig -orous
approach to public spending'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P91  Executive, Legislative and General Government.
</IN>
