<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 93 / Parliament and Politics: Pause in Maastricht debate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MPs are to have at least a week off from debating the Maastricht bill - but
the government denied that it was having to be slowed deliberately to fit in
with Denmark's plans for its second referendum.
As the Commons last night began the 11th committee day on the bill,
ministers confirmed privately that the final vote by MPs before it goes to
the House of Lords will not take place before the Danish poll, now fixed for
May 18.
Yet they insisted that the bill was proceeding through the Commons as
planned and its timing had not been affected by the Danish announcement.
'We think that we are making reasonable progress on the Maastricht bill, in
line with the sort of progress that we expected to make,' said one cabinet
minister.
In the Commons Mr Tony Newton, leader of the house, announced a programme of
business for next week that excludes debate on the Maastricht bill. No
decisions have been taken about when the committee stage will resume.
Government managers argued that a backlog of business had built up which
required debate and that it was always the intention to vary the pace of the
bill's progress.
</TEXT>
