<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 93 / Parliament and Politics: Retirement change to be staged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SOCIAL security ministers are drawing up plans to soften the impact of a
planned rise to 65 in the female state retirement age. They intend to delay
the increase for a decade - and warn that Britain will lose to economic
competitors if the change is blocked.
Under proposals being considered by the department, the retirement age for
women would remain at the current 60 for 10 years. After that the qualifying
age would rise by 12 months each year for five years.
Mr Peter Lilley, the social security secretary, has begun consultations with
other cabinet colleagues and is expected to publish before the summer a
white paper on pension equalisation.
The department is acutely aware of the strong political impact of the
planned rise, and the reaction of women employees. But they are preparing to
counter that by arguing that no woman currently in her fifties would be
affected.
Figures prepared by the department will be used to argue that UK companies
could be severely disadvantaged if male and female retirement ages are not
equalised at 65.
Maintaining the status quo would, as the population ages, impose an
increasing burden on the Treasury - and on companies who set their
retirement ages in line with the state.
A review by the social security department shows that in Germany, retirement
ages are to be equalised at 65 by 2012 and that over the next two decades
Luxembourg, the Netherlands and Spain, will equalise at 65. Denmark is to
equalise at 67 and the US is expected to move to 67 by the year 2027.
The exception is Japan, which is to equalise at 60 by 2000 but the social
security department believes the country may also move towards 65 by a later
date.
</TEXT>
