<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 93 / Construction is set to decline further
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UK CONSTRUCTION output looks set to decline even further this year, judging
by an industry workload survey published yesterday.
The results of a questionnaire covering more than 2,000 quantity surveyors
showed that orders last year fell by 18 per cent to their lowest level since
1985, when the survey began.
The findings, published by the Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors, are
worrying for the rest of the industry. Much quantity surveying work, such as
that of architects, occurs early in the construction process. Surveyors'
orders therefore provide a good guide to future workloads of construction
companies and building material suppliers.
Demand is likely to be worse for private commercial development where large
numbers of empty office buildings are expected to remain on the market even
when the economy recovers.
Mr Christopher Vickers, a senior partner at EC Harris, one of the largest
firms of quantity surveyors, said: 'These gloomy figures show the
construction industry still faces an uphill struggle. Any recovery is going
to be long and very difficult, particularly for smaller practices.'
The survey showed that orders fell by 5 per cent during the final three
months of last year compared with the previous quarter.
The number of staff employed by quantity surveyors declined by 8.5 per cent
in 1992 after falls in the previous two years.
The institution said the recession had hit south-east England hardest, with
a 26 per cent drop in surveyors' workloads last year. Further reductions in
orders occurred in south-west England, the Midlands and Wales. Meanwhile,
orders in Scotland and Northern Ireland, which had avoided the worst of the
recession, had begun to decline.
</TEXT>
