<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 93 / Third of employers 'impose pay freeze'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ABOUT one in three of employers introduced pay freezes in the final quarter
of last year, according to the Confederation of British Industry's latest
pay databank figures.
Over the same period, which saw Britain's withdrawal from the European
exchange rate mechanism and a spate of large redundancy announcements, the
CBI recorded average manufacturing pay settlements at only 2.8 per cent.
Pay awards in the service sector in that quarter were 3.2 per cent.
The government will welcome the further squeeze on private sector pay in
view of its 1.5 per cent pay limit for the public sector.
Although some of the low awards in the final quarter of last year might have
been affected by the uncertainty following withdrawal from the ERM,
subsequent settlements do not suggest that the downward trend has ended.
National Westminster and Lloyds Bank announced last month that staff will be
receiving no general pay increase, and the national pay deal for the
footwear industry was 2.5 per cent.
The latest settlements will mean further strong downward pressure on average
earnings, which were still rising at an annualised rate of 5 per cent in
November for the whole economy.
Unit labour costs in manufacturing, rising at only 0.5 per cent in November
could fall even further. The latest CBI figures say that manufacturers'
productivity rose 3.9 per cent in the second half of last year, while basic
pay awards averaged 3.5 per cent.
Other pay analysts expressed some scepticism about the CBI pay freeze
figures.
Mr Alistair Hatchett, of the pay analysts Incomes Data Services, said that
IDS had found that there was a slight increase in the incidence of freezes
but it affected only about one settlement in six.
</TEXT>
