<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 93 / OECD says coal closures will cut fuel costs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE planned closure of coal mines should lead to cheaper energy and cut
environmental costs, the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and
Development said.
The latest OECD survey of the UK economy says taxes on fuel should be more
closely related to the amount of pollution they cause.
In a special section on the environment, the survey says there are
'inconsistencies' in the tax treatment of specific fuels which act against
goals of reducing pollution.
It adds: 'Removing artificial barriers to fuel substitution and conservation
and establishing energy prices which better reflect potential environmental
damage are likely to be the most cost-efficient means of protecting the
environment.'
The OECD suggests measures to relate taxes and other charges on vehicles
more directly to road use, rather than ownership of cars or lorries. As well
as reducing pollutants such as nitrogen oxides from vehicle exhausts, such
'road pricing' mechanisms could help reduce traffic congestion and energy
use.
The study says Britain's heavy dependence on burning coal for electricity
generation contributes to the large volumes of carbon dioxide and sulphur
oxides entering the atmosphere from the UK, at rates above the European
Community average. It welcomes the projected rapid substitution of natural
gas for coal in a new power stations.
Distortions in environment-related tax and pricing mechanisms highlighted by
the OECD include:
Household energy use is exempt from value added taxation, while investment
in energy saving is subject to VAT at the normal rate, factors which do
nothing to encourage energy saving.
Public transport receives relatively low government subsidies, while private
parking provided by employers is exempt from taxation as a benefit in kind.
Few households have meters to control the water supply, which may promote
profligate use of water.
OECD urges tax rise, Page 8
</TEXT>
