<HEADLINE>
FT  05 FEB 93 / Tory rebels state their pit demands
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TORY OPPONENTS of the government's pit closures programme have signalled
that they may be ready to accept a new strategy for the industry which would
rescue fewer pits than the number implied in last week's report from the
Commons trade and industry committee.
An FT survey of the Tory backbenchers most likely to rebel if too few pits
are saved indicated that a plan to rescue between 12 and 14 threatened coal
mines may be enough to stave off defeat in the Commons on the issue.
But the potential rebels hold a wide range of views, and some hardliners
insist that up to 20 of the 31 pits must be rescued. Nevertheless, an
assurance that private operators would be able to take over the running of
any pits British Coal decided to close would help appease rebels.
The government could be defeated if as few as 11 of its backbenchers voted
against it in the Commons debate on the energy white paper to be published
later this month.
Among the most difficult to satisfy is Mrs Ann Winterton, MP for Congleton,
who spoke of sparing a number 'in the high teens.' Mr Stephen Day, MP for
Cheadle, described the trade and industry committee report as 'the bottom
line'.
Others have a lower threshold. Mr David Nicholson, the MP for Taunton, who
said he had attended meetings of the 30-strong coal group of Tory MPs, said
he would vote against the government 'only if the government appeared
suicidal.' He added: 'Anything below 10 and we come into abstention or
voting against.'
Mr Spencer Batiste, MP for Elmet and another coal group member, said he was
'looking for a minimum of 10 to 15 pits in the context of British Coal' with
remaining pits offered for sale. He was likely to support the government
unless it proposed an additional market significantly below 10m tonnes per
year, he indicated.
Mrs Elizabeth Peacock, the MP for Batley and Spen who has been among the
most prominent Tory coal campaigners, said she would be unlikely to back
proposals to save between 10 and 12 pits. 'I think we could get an
additional 30m tonnes per year with a subsidy of just short of Pounds 300m
over five years.'
Sir Richard Body, MP for Holland with Boston and 'theoretically' a coal
group member, said he had abstained when MPs debated the pit closure
programme last October because it was 'disgraceful' that any group of
employees should be treated 'in this way without consultation'. Many of
these concerns had been addressed, he indicated.
The soundings suggest that Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry
secretary, may win a majority for a package which rescues fewer pits than
the committee implied.
He may be reluctant to pitch such controversial proposals so close to the
minimum that MPs regard as acceptable, however.
Mr Winston Churchill, one of the leaders of the coal group, has warned that
Mr Heseltine 'cannot afford to lead the government to defeat on this issue'.
Calculations of the number needed to defeat the government are complicated
by the presence of the 13 Ulster unionists. Last year the abstention of
eight Unionists helped to ensure that a Labour amendment was defeated in
spite of a rebellion by six Tories.
If all 13 unionist MPs abstained when the white paper is debated, the number
of Tory rebels needed to defeat the government would rise to 18.
 ---------------------------------------------
